The R-squared (R²) value typically ranges from 0 to 1 (though it can also be negative in some cases, e.g., when the model is worse than a simple mean prediction). Here’s what different R² values indicate:

Guidelines for Interpreting R²:
	•	R² ≈ 1:
	•	The model explains almost all the variability in the target variable. This is ideal but rare in real-world data, especially noisy data like claims or severity models.
	•	R² ≈ 0.5 to 0.8:
	•	A strong model for most practical purposes, especially in domains like insurance and regression tasks where data variability is often high.
	•	R² ≈ 0.3 to 0.5:
	•	The model explains some variability but may still miss important factors. Depending on the application, this could be acceptable, especially for noisy data.
	•	R² < 0.3:
	•	Weak explanatory power. This suggests the model needs improvement (e.g., better features, tuning, or addressing issues like data leakage).
	•	R² ≈ 0 or negative:
	•	The model fails to explain the variability in the data (or performs worse than simply predicting the mean). This is problematic and typically indicates a fundamental issue with the model or data.

What R² Should Be for Your Severity Model?
	•	Severity models in insurance often deal with highly skewed and noisy data. As a result:
	•	R² between 0.3 and 0.7 is typically considered reasonable.
	•	A lower R² can still be acceptable if the model demonstrates good performance on other metrics like MAE or RMSE, which directly reflect prediction accuracy.

Focus on MAE and business relevance alongside R², as insurance severity models tend to prioritize the magnitude of prediction error over purely maximizing R².

